page.text: Rowan University’s Rohrer College of Business is planning to construct a new facility on the location of
the existing commuter Lot A, located on Mullica Hill Road in Glassboro, New Jersey. The 110,000 facility
will replace the current facility and include classroom space, student meeting spaces, faculty offices, a
student business hatchery, and a large meeting space to allow for the current enrollment of the college to
double to 2170 students. The facility will also include a student business hatchery and a large auditorium
The following intersections were analyzed in this study:
Mullica Hill Road (US Route 322) and Joseph L Bowe Boulevard
Joseph L Bowe Boulevard and North Campus Drive
Mullica Hill Road (US Route 322) and Lot A Driveways
The performance of the study intersections under existing conditions was evaluated through a qualitative
measure of operating conditions called Levels of Service. Six levels of service (LOS) are defined with
letter designations from A to F, with Level of Service A representing delays up to ten seconds and Level
of Service F indicating delays exceeding fifty seconds for unsignalized intersections and eighty seconds
for signalized intersections. Level of Service C or better is considered acceptable, with a threshold of
Level of Service D in urban areas.
NJDOT has classified Glassboro as an urban area.
The proposed is anticipated to increase the amount of trips to the area by 185 (145 entering and
40 exiting) during the AM peak and 185 (60 entering and 125 exiting) during the PM peak. The
majority of these trips are anticipated to utilize commuter lots M-1, C and D.
Under the existing and No-Build conditions, the signalized intersection of Mullica Hill Road and
Bowe Boulevard operates at acceptable Levels of Service, operating with overall intersection Levels
of Service B or better during both peak hours.
Under the 2013 existing conditions, the westbound left turns from North Campus Drive onto Bowe
Boulevard operates at LOS F with 69.9 seconds of delay during the AM peak period, and 118
seconds of delay during the PM peak period.
Under the Build conditions, the signalized intersection of Mullica Hill Road and Bowe Boulevard
operates at LOS E with 69.8 seconds of delay during the AM peak and LOS C with 32.9 seconds
of delay during the PM peak. The eastbound left movement operates at LOS F with 109.7
seconds of delay and the westbound movement operates at LOS E with 64.2 seconds of delay
Under the existing conditions and build conditions, the intersection of North Campus Drive and Bowe
Boulevard meets the peak hour signal warrant in the PM peak period.
The increased traffic on Mullica Hill Road and Bowe Boulevard from the proposed expansion of the
College of Engineering and the Rohrer College of Business results in the signalized intersection of Mullica
Hill Road at Bowe Boulevard operating with an unacceptable overall intersection delay and Level of
Service during the AM Peak period. Given the roadway characteristics, the proximity of adjacent
driveways, and the complexities involved with physically modifying signals on a State roadway it is
recommended that the intersection be mitigated through timing modifications including the increasing the
cycle length and optimizing the splits while maintaining the existing phasing.
It is also recommended that consideration be given to the construction of a signal at the intersection of
Bowe Boulevard and North Campus drive along with the addition of a 100’ northbound right turn lane.
This would greatly reduce delays on North Campus Drive during both the AM and PM peak periods. A 90

page.text: The following is a due diligence report which documents the results of an investigation of transportation
impacts associated with the proposed development of the new Rohrer College of Business facility to be
on the current location of commuter Lot A. Lot A is on Mullica Hill Road, with a right in and a right out
driveway on Mullica Hill road, and a connection to North campus Drive Chestnut Branch Drive.
The Rohrer College of Business is planning on opening its new facility in the winter of 2016.
The proposed development includes construction of an 110,000 square foot multi-level facility. This new
building will accommodate current and future enrollment within the college. The current facility, Bruce
Hall, is unable to accommodate the growing amount of students within the college. The new facility will
enable the college to increase enrollment to 2170 students in the college.
There proposed development does not include any new parking facilities. It will cut the available parking
in Lot A by half and it It is anticipated that the new trips generated by the expansion and the displaced
trips will utilize the existing parking lots within a quarter mile of the site (Lot C, Lot D, Lot M-1, Lot A, and
Lot A-1) or utilize the campus shuttle system.
The project area is illustrated in FIGURE 1 and the conceptual site plan for the Rohrer College of
Business site is shown in FIGURE 2.
Rowan University’s College of Engineering is also planning on expanding their current facility, Rowan
Hall, located on North Campus Drive approximately 500’ from the intersection of North Campus Drive and
Bowe Boulevard. The 90,500 square foot addition will enable the college to double their faculty and
students. The current enrollment is 1200 students and 35 faculty members and is anticipated to double
as a result of the expansion. The expansion will be completed in the winter of 2016.
The study area for this analysis includes Mullica Hill Road (US Route 322), Joseph L Bowe Boulevard,
and North Campus Drive. The following intersections are included in the study area and were counted on
Wednesday, September 25, 2013 during the weekday AM peak period (7:00 AM – 9:00 AM) and during
the PM peak period (4:00 PM - 6:00 PM):

page.text: Mullica Hill Road (US 322) – Mullica Hill Road is an east-west oriented urban principal arterial.
Mullica Hill Road is 36’ wide and designated as two-way. On both sides of the intersection of
Joseph L Bowe Boulevard, Mullica Hill Road contains one 11’ travel lane and one 7’ shoulder in
each direction. At its intersection with Joseph L Bowe Boulevard, Mullica Hill Road has an
eastbound left turn lane. Sidewalk is provided on the north side of the Mullica Hill Road east of
Joseph L Bowe Boulevard and west of Joseph L Bowe Boulevard to the driveway for the Beau
Rivage Townhomes (approximately 100’). The posted speed limit on Mullica Hill Road is 35 mph.
Joseph L Bowe Boulevard – Joseph L Bowe Boulevard (Bowe Boulevard) is a north-south
oriented urban major collector. Bowe Boulevard is designated two-way with one travel lane for
each direction. North of the intersection with North Campus Drive, Bowe Boulevard is 42’ wide
with 21’ wide travel lanes. South of the intersection with North Campus drive, Bowe Boulevard
ranges from 42’-48’ wide, with 21’-24’ wide travel lanes. At its intersection with Mullica Hill Road,
southbound Bowe Boulevard has one right lane and one left/through lane. At the intersection of
Bowe Boulevard and North Campus Drive, southbound Bowe Boulevard has one exclusive left
turn lane and a through lane. Southbound of Mullica Hill Road, Bowe Boulevard becomes
Harvard Road. North of Carpenter Street, Bowe Boulevard becomes Barge Boulevard.
Sidewalks are provided on both sides of Bowe Boulevard, and the posted speed limit is 25mph.
North Campus Drive – North Campus Drive is an east-west oriented local road. North Campus
Drive is 25’ wide and contains one 12.5’ travel lane in each direction. There are Rowan
University shuttle stops along the south side of the street. At the intersection with Bowe
Boulevard, North Campus Drive has a westbound left turn lane and a westbound right turn lane.
Sidewalks are provided on both sides of the street, and the posted speed limit is 15mph.
Mullica Hill Road (US 322) and Joseph L Bowe Boulevard – The intersection of Mullica Hill
Road and Bowe Boulevard is a four-leg signalized intersection operating with three-phase timing
and a 60 second cycle length. Eastbound Mullica Hill Road has a leading left turn phase. The
eastbound approach has one left turn lane and one through lane. The westbound approach has
one through lane, but many of the right turning vehicles use the shoulder as a separate lane. The
northbound approach has one through lane; the southbound approach has one right turn lane
and one left/through lane. Both streets allow for two way traffic. Sidewalks are present on the
north side of Mullica Hill Road, and on the east side of Harvard Road. Pedestrian signals,
crosswalks, and A.D.A ramps are provided for all pedestrian approaches at this intersection.
Mullica Hill Road (US 322) and Lot A Driveways – The intersection of Mullica Hill Road and the
Lot A Driveways is a three leg unsignalized intersection. The two driveways of the lot are 150’
apart. The western driveway is exit to the lot, and the eastern driveway is the entrance. Mullica

page.text: considered acceptable in urban areas. Levels of Service are determined through analysis procedures
outlined in the 2010 Highway Capacity Manual (Transportation Research Board, Washington, D.C.).
Levels of Service for signalized intersections are based on average delay experienced by motorists
passing the intersection. The delay is based on the results of the capacity analysis (rate of demand flow
capacity) and other important variables such as quality of progression, cycle length and ratio of green
Levels of service for unsignalized intersections are defined in terms of delay to vehicles entering from the
side road and turning left from a major road. Delay is a function of the capacity of the approach and
degree of saturation. The capacity is based on the distribution of gaps in the major street traffic stream,
driver judgment in selecting a gap through which to execute the desired maneuver, and follow-up time
required by each driver in a queue. The Level of Service Criteria for signalized and unsignalized
intersections is provided in APPENDIX B.
The operational analyses of the study intersections under all conditions were performed using the
Synchro/Simtraffic Version 8.0 software. The levels of service and delays are based on the 2010 Highway
Capacity Manual (HCM2010) published by the Transportation Research Board, Washington D.C. The
HCM sets forth nationally accepted standards regarding traffic operations and capacity analysis. The
queue length analysis was conducted utilizing Simtraffic software.

text.b: Intersection of Mullica Hill Road (US Route 322) and Bowe Boulevard

page.text: The increased traffic on Mullica Hill Road and Bowe Boulevard from the proposed expansion of the
College of Engineering and the Rohrer College of Business results in the signalized intersection of Mullica
Hill Road at Bowe Boulevard operating with an unacceptable overall intersection delay and Level of
Service during the AM Peak period. The eastbound left movement operates at LOS F with 109.7 seconds
of delay and the westbound movement operates at LOS E with 64.2 seconds of delay during the AM peak
period. The mitigation options for the intersection include the optimization of the splits and cycle length of
the existing signal while maintaining the existing phasing and geometric improvements to increase
capacity with the addition of a westbound right turn lane and timing modifications. Given the roadway
characteristics, the proximity of adjacent driveways, and the complexities involved with physically
modifying signals on a State roadway it is recommended that the intersection be mitigated through timing
Increasing the existing cycle length at the intersection from 60 seconds to 90 seconds will allow for
additional green time to be provided to both the eastbound lead left turn phase lane and the westbound
approach while maintaining the minimum northbound/southbound phasing as required for pedestrian
crossings. The resulting intersection delay is reduced to 52.9 (LOS D) during the Am peak period
However, there will still be movements operating at LOS E.
In order to fully mitigate the impact of the proposed development on the intersection of Mullica Hill Road
and Bowe Boulevard the number of turning movements from Mullica Hill Road to Bowe Boulevard needs
to be reduced. The current commuter lots M-1, C and Lot D are anticipated to be utilized by the new trips
generated by the proposed development. The development of additional parking east of the proposed
development on Mullica Hill Road or the determination through a parking study that the new trips would
displace existing trips from these lots would reduce the impact at the intersection.
If necessary, the modification of the existing geometry at the intersection of Mullica Hill Road and Bowe
Boulevard would consist of the widening of the north side of the east approach in order to provide an 75’
westbound right turn lane. The westbound right turn lane would increase capacity at the intersection and
the corresponding analysis would result in acceptable overall and approach levels of service and delays.

Left turns are permitted from the state highway on Access Level 4 segments but typically require left turn

recommended that left turns into the proposed site from Mullica Hill Road continue to prohibited, as it is
Access from Mullica Hill Road (US 322) eastbound will be made from North Campus Drive via Chestnut

segments. Left turns are currently permitted from the existing parking lot located in front of the Heating
Plant on Mullica Hill Road (US 322). The reduced parking area of the proposed site is not anticipated to

size of the remaining parking lot, a number of left turns could be made effectively from the proposed
driveway onto Mullica Hill Road eastbound, reducing the number of vehicles utilizing the Chestnut Branch
Drive connection. There is still a potential of traffic on Mullica Hill Road affecting the efficiency of a left
turn egress from the proposed site. Therefore it is recommended that, upon the determination of a final
parking lot size or the new development, that further consideration be given to permitting a left egress
from the onto Mullica Hill Road.
